00:49:49.880 --> 00:49:53.580
Regulation Expands the Landscape of Targetable Suppressors."

889
00:49:54.620 --> 00:49:58.460
Thanks very much to the organizers for this opportunity to speak about our

890
00:49:58.540 --> 00:49:58.780
work.

891
00:49:59.600 --> 00:50:03.260
My name is Bill DiPlas, and I'm a physician scientist in radiation oncology at

892
00:50:03.320 --> 00:50:07.240
Sloan Kettering, and I'm excited to discuss our ongoing work in

893
00:50:07.280 --> 00:50:11.180
understanding the regulation of this pathway alternative lengthening of telomeres,

894
00:50:11.300 --> 00:50:12.420
otherwise known as ALT.

895
00:50:14.180 --> 00:50:15.300
These are my disclosures.

896
00:50:16.780 --> 00:50:20.760
So telomere maintenance mechanisms are universal to cancer, a hallmark

897
00:50:20.840 --> 00:50:22.520
allowing for replicative immortality.

898
00:50:23.220 --> 00:50:25.749
While the majority of cancers activate telomerase,

899
00:50:26.960 --> 00:50:30.250
whose activity allows for addition of telomeric repeats to the ends of chromosomes,

900
00:50:30.840 --> 00:50:33.800
approximately 10% of cancers use this ALT pathway.

901
00:50:34.680 --> 00:50:38.080
This is telomerase independent, and it relies on recombination

902
00:50:39.300 --> 00:50:41.360
to elongate telomeres.

903
00:50:43.240 --> 00:50:46.160
And so ALT is specifically present in several key

904
00:50:46.200 --> 00:50:49.860
histologies. These include malignant gliomas, pancreatic neuroendocrine

905
00:50:49.900 --> 00:50:53.080
tumors, as well as soft tissue sarcomas and

906
00:50:53.140 --> 00:50:55.940
osteosarcoma and neuroblastoma.

907
00:50:57.680 --> 00:51:01.420
From sequencing studies over the past decades, ALT tumors have been found to be

908
00:51:01.460 --> 00:51:03.560
associated with a number of ALT drivers.

909
00:51:04.520 --> 00:51:08.210
Namely, these include loss of function mutations in ATRX and DAXX,

910
00:51:08.560 --> 00:51:12.060
which lead to a loss of protein expression, which I'm showing on the right here.

911
00:51:13.700 --> 00:51:17.520
And in addition, what's known about these is that they normally

912
00:51:17.560 --> 00:51:21.240
deposit H3.3 at the telomeres, and this helps to protect against

913
00:51:21.360 --> 00:51:22.880
replication stress and recombination.

914
00:51:25.000 --> 00:51:28.240
There are a number of key hallmarks used for ALT phenotyping,

915
00:51:28.960 --> 00:51:32.140
and to identify tumors with this phenotype.

916
00:51:32.679 --> 00:51:35.120
And also namely to track ALT activity.

917
00:51:35.680 --> 00:51:36.000
And so

918
00:51:36.800 --> 00:51:37.360
these include

919
00:51:38.600 --> 00:51:42.500
long heterogeneous telomeres that are detected by denatured FISH, as well

920
00:51:42.560 --> 00:51:46.260
as ALT-associated PML bodies, otherwise known as APBs, which are made up of

921
00:51:46.800 --> 00:51:50.240
PML protein that is simulated to form these hubs of recombination

922
00:51:50.740 --> 00:51:52.880
that are really at the core of ALT recombination.

923
00:51:53.660 --> 00:51:55.980
These contain repair factors along with

924
00:51:57.840 --> 00:52:00.340
telomere ends that are critical, again, for the ALT

925
00:52:00.440 --> 00:52:04.340
activity. Lastly, single-strand DNA present

926
00:52:04.360 --> 00:52:08.280
on telomere gaps and C-circles are also critical to ALT activity

927
00:52:08.300 --> 00:52:11.360
and specific to it, and these can be detected by native FISH.

928
00:52:11.480 --> 00:52:13.300
This is also known as SSTOC.

929
00:52:15.980 --> 00:52:19.600
And so in terms of the underlying mechanisms of ALT, a number of factors have been

930
00:52:19.640 --> 00:52:23.420
implicated in this pathway, and as I said before, most of them are related to DNA

931
00:52:23.460 --> 00:52:27.380
repair and recombination. However, the exact mechanism of this pathway is

932
00:52:27.420 --> 00:52:30.589
not fully understood. What we do know is that all telomeres are prone to

933
00:52:30.880 --> 00:52:32.080
significant replication stress,

934
00:52:32.980 --> 00:52:36.220
usually due to the accumulation of secondary structures of the telomeres that make

935
00:52:36.240 --> 00:52:37.240
them difficult to replicate.

936
00:52:38.100 --> 00:52:41.740
And ALT seems to have similarities to break-induced replication or

937
00:52:41.820 --> 00:52:42.260
BIR.

938
00:52:43.200 --> 00:52:46.560
And so we've been able to map through the studies of many

939
00:52:47.160 --> 00:52:49.840
groups, a number of ALT promoters and ALT suppressors.

940
00:52:50.380 --> 00:52:52.920
I've underlined some of the most important ones.

941
00:52:53.500 --> 00:52:57.029
Bloom, which is a part of the BTR complex, helps resolve recombination

942
00:52:57.180 --> 00:53:01.060
intermediates, and also FANCM, which resolves R-loops at

943
00:53:01.080 --> 00:53:03.339
telomeres and prevents fork stalling.

944
00:53:04.560 --> 00:53:04.700
So

945
00:53:05.520 --> 00:53:08.500
there's a lot of clinical interest in targeting these, and most of the clinical

946
00:53:08.520 --> 00:53:11.800
interest is in targeting the suppressors, which usually lead to a hyper-ALT

947
00:53:11.840 --> 00:53:13.100
phenotype and then cell death.

948
00:53:15.740 --> 00:53:17.320
And so I like this visualization of this.

949
00:53:17.330 --> 00:53:21.100
So to maintain ALT activity, it requires a balance of these factors.

950
00:53:21.380 --> 00:53:22.140
And so

951
00:53:23.060 --> 00:53:26.290
you need some level of baseline DNA replication stress to initiate telomere

952
00:53:26.320 --> 00:53:29.570
elongation. However, when this is too high, the balance is tipped towards this

953
00:53:29.600 --> 00:53:33.100
hyper-ALT phenotype, which is lethal in cells.

954
00:53:34.660 --> 00:53:37.940
And again, there's a lot of recent clinical interest in this.

955
00:53:39.100 --> 00:53:41.360
As you can see from notable papers

956
00:53:42.820 --> 00:53:45.300
that showed that ATR is a target in alternative lengthening of telomeres

957
00:53:46.120 --> 00:53:50.090
positive cells, and usually again, leading towards tipping this balance towards

958
00:53:50.120 --> 00:53:53.870
the hyper-ALT phenotype. And this was recently published

959
00:53:54.060 --> 00:53:57.280
this past year, a patient that was treated with an ATR inhibitor with metastatic

960
00:53:57.300 --> 00:53:59.860
melanoma who had an exceptional response to the drug.

961
00:53:59.880 --> 00:54:03.730
And so clearly, there's a lot of work done to further identify novel factors in

962
00:54:03.760 --> 00:54:07.640
this area. In line with this, our hypothesis was

963
00:54:08.720 --> 00:54:12.400
if we could leverage ALT phenotypes in the context of genome-wide screening to map

964
00:54:12.620 --> 00:54:16.000
the regulatory landscape of alternative lengthening of telomeres in cancer.

965
00:54:17.640 --> 00:54:17.920
And so

966
00:54:19.240 --> 00:54:22.000
to do this, we realized we needed to develop a new tool.

967
00:54:22.580 --> 00:54:24.900
Native FISH, which I mentioned before, is ALT specific

968
00:54:26.020 --> 00:54:29.460
and tracks with ALT activity. And as you can see below from cells growing on a

969
00:54:29.520 --> 00:54:33.380
dish, when you knock down Bloom, it has a

970
00:54:34.020 --> 00:54:35.660
lead to a decreased phenotype of ALT

971
00:54:36.860 --> 00:54:40.380
FISH. And then when you knock out FANCM, you have an increased

972
00:54:40.420 --> 00:54:44.130
hyper-ALT phenotype compared to the NTC control, and this is in U2OS.

973
00:54:46.500 --> 00:54:50.150
And so what we decided to do is take this native FISH approach, and after

974
00:54:50.160 --> 00:54:53.870
significant optimization, develop it into a flow-based readout of

975
00:54:53.880 --> 00:54:56.480
single-cell ALT activity. We're calling this Alt-Flow-FISH.

976
00:54:57.000 --> 00:55:00.060
And using this, we were able to show that we can discriminate these same

977
00:55:00.100 --> 00:55:03.700
promoters from ALT suppressors, but this time in a

978
00:55:04.220 --> 00:55:05.720
flow-based manner and at scale.

979
00:55:08.080 --> 00:55:11.870
Given this, we expanded this to a genome-wide CRISPR screen in two ALT lines,

980
00:55:12.360 --> 00:55:15.860
U2OS and RP-ALT, using the genome-wide library TKOv3.

981
00:55:16.470 --> 00:55:20.160
Following selection, we performed Alt-Flow-FISH only after four days and

982
00:55:20.220 --> 00:55:23.940
sorted the highest and lowest populations in terms of native FISH

983
00:55:24.000 --> 00:55:27.590
signal. We did this in an effort to specifically map ALT

984
00:55:27.660 --> 00:55:31.510
promoters and suppressors, rather than what you're probably used to seeing,

985
00:55:31.560 --> 00:55:34.990
which is a typical viability screen using these CRISPR genome-wide

986
00:55:35.020 --> 00:55:38.844
approaches.And so

987
00:55:38.984 --> 00:55:42.344
interestingly, what we found is that when we

988
00:55:43.064 --> 00:55:46.964
intentionally chose the early time point specifically to try to find both

989
00:55:46.984 --> 00:55:48.424
essential and non-essential genes.

990
00:55:48.444 --> 00:55:50.654
And interestingly, what we found is that if you map out

991
00:55:51.644 --> 00:55:55.464
genes that were labeled as suppressors and promoters, actually

992
00:55:55.524 --> 00:55:58.644
among the suppressors, there were many essential genes that would have otherwise

993
00:55:58.664 --> 00:56:00.744
been missed if we had used viability as an endpoint.

994
00:56:04.004 --> 00:56:05.924
And then when we look at this

995
00:56:07.024 --> 00:56:11.004
across the genome, we see that a number of controls

996
00:56:11.264 --> 00:56:15.204
come out as validation that our screen is working, including the BTR complex,

997
00:56:15.264 --> 00:56:18.944
as I mentioned before, as a promoter and as a suppressor of FANCM.

998
00:56:19.974 --> 00:56:22.754
And what's interesting from this is also that we found that there's a kind of a

999
00:56:22.764 --> 00:56:26.444
downward shift of the curve, where there are many more ALT suppressors

1000
00:56:26.504 --> 00:56:30.204
identified from this assay, which may be also due to some technical reasons for

1001
00:56:30.244 --> 00:56:31.224
detection purposes.

1002
00:56:32.864 --> 00:56:36.524
We did pathway analysis on all the hits from this screen and found that a number of

1003
00:56:36.544 --> 00:56:40.344
factors related to DNA repair, replication, and cell cycle, but also novel

1004
00:56:40.384 --> 00:56:43.394
pathways, including the proteasome and fanconi anemia pathways.

1005
00:56:45.024 --> 00:56:48.784
And so I've shown these two here, and we chose to focus on

1006
00:56:48.824 --> 00:56:52.524
these two key pathways because they were less well-characterized in terms of their

1007
00:56:52.544 --> 00:56:56.044
role in ALT. I'll be focusing primarily today on our work related to the

1008
00:56:56.084 --> 00:56:59.924
proteasome, just due to time. And notably, among

1009
00:56:59.944 --> 00:57:02.604
these proteasome hits, we found both structural components of the proteasome,

1010
00:57:02.704 --> 00:57:05.794
including PSMB1, PSMB5, 6, among others.

1011
00:57:05.844 --> 00:57:09.774
But we also found akirin 2, which was recently identified as

1012
00:57:09.774 --> 00:57:13.764
a factor responsible for nuclear import of the proteasome, which would be in line

1013
00:57:13.804 --> 00:57:16.084
with what we might expect for this phenotype as well.

1014
00:57:17.724 --> 00:57:21.504
And so we first independently designed guides targeting the top hits from the

1015
00:57:21.564 --> 00:57:24.584
