1937
01:49:18.024 --> 01:49:18.364
Mm-hmm.

1938
01:49:18.784 --> 01:49:19.004
So

1939
01:49:20.524 --> 01:49:21.764
are you envisioning

1940
01:49:22.684 --> 01:49:26.664
this as a sensitization, so it will be open for all, or

1941
01:49:26.804 --> 01:49:29.904
are you envisioning this maybe as a translational

1942
01:49:30.424 --> 01:49:32.824
potential for overcoming resistance?

1943
01:49:33.244 --> 01:49:35.444
Yeah. I think that's something really important.

1944
01:49:35.484 --> 01:49:39.184
You're talking about PARP inhibitors, which upon DNA

1945
01:49:39.264 --> 01:49:43.184
damage, and you see for single-strand breaks, if PARP is inhibited, it's not

1946
01:49:43.264 --> 01:49:47.064
able to perform, or PARP1 is not able to perform its function in base

1947
01:49:47.144 --> 01:49:50.874
excision repair, and then in cells that are

1948
01:49:50.984 --> 01:49:54.844
HR deficient, that's the key that because you're inhibiting that, then

1949
01:49:54.904 --> 01:49:58.464
those cells ultimately to death. And I think maybe targeting something like

1950
01:49:58.524 --> 01:50:02.264
EYF4 to kind of induce a homologous recombination deficient state

1951
01:50:02.544 --> 01:50:06.484
in combination therapy, and then further exploiting this vulnerability

1952
01:50:06.544 --> 01:50:10.484
is a really interesting application and type of therapy that is

1953
01:50:10.524 --> 01:50:11.924
definitely worth exploring.

1954
01:50:12.844 --> 01:50:13.924
So yeah, I think that's really interesting.

1955
01:50:13.964 --> 01:50:14.064
Yeah.

1956
01:50:14.504 --> 01:50:14.664
Mm-hmm.

1957
01:50:14.784 --> 01:50:15.703
I think so too.

1958
01:50:17.044 --> 01:50:18.883
The phosphorylation,

1959
